  <title>Example</title>
  

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find five rational numbers between <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{3}{5}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        There are infinite rational numbers between <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{3}{5}</m>. 
        To find out <m>5</m> rational numbers between <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> and<m>\frac{3}{5}</m>, 
        we will multiply and divide both the numbers with 5+1=6 (or any number greater than 5), 
        i.e., <me>\frac{2}{5} \times \frac{6}{6} =  \frac{12}{30}</me> and, 
        <me>\frac{3}{5} \times \frac{6}{6} =  \frac{18}{30}</me>. 
        The numbers in between <m>\frac{12}{30}</m> and <m>\frac{18}{30}</m>  will be rational and will fall 
        between <m>\frac{2}{5}</m>  and <m>\frac{3}{5}</m>. 
        Hence, <m>\frac{13}{30}</m>, <m>\frac{14}{30}</m>, <m>\frac{15}{30}</m>, <m>\frac{16}{30}</m>, <m>\frac{17}{30}</m> 
        are these numbers.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        State whether the following statements are true or false. Give reasons for your answers.
     
      <ol marker ="i.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Every natural number is a whole number.
          </p>
          </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every integer is a whole number.
          </p>
         </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every rational number is a whole number.
          </p>
            </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every irrational number is a real number.
          </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Every real number is an irrational number.
              </p>
            </li>
                 </ol>
                </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
                <term>True</term> whole numbers have all the elements of natural numbers and zero. 
                <alert>Natural numbers</alert>: Numbers starting from 1 to infinity (without fractions or decimals).
              </p>
             </li>
             <li>
              <p>
                <term>False</term> Every whole number is an integer; however, every integer is not a whole number.
               <alert> Integers</alert> are set of numbers that contain positive, negative and 0; 
               excluding fractional and decimal numbers.
              </p>
             </li>
             <li>
              <p>
                <term>False</term> All whole numbers are rational, however, all rational numbers are not whole numbers. 
                <alert> Whole numbers</alert>: Numbers starting from 0 to infinity (without fractions or decimals).
               <alert> Rational numbers</alert>: All numbers in the form <m>p/q</m>, where p and q are integers and <m>q \neq 0</m>.
               </p>
             </li>
             <li>
              <p>
                <term>True</term> Every irrational number is a real number, however, every real number is not an irrational number.
                <alert>Irrational Numbers</alert>: They cannot be written in the <m>\frac{p}{q}</m>, where p and q are integers and <m>q \neq 0</m>.
                <alert>Real numbers</alert>: The collection of both rational and irrational numbers are known as real numbers.
              </p>
             </li>
             <li>
              <p>
                <term>False</term> Real numbers include both irrational and rational numbers. 
                Therefore, every real number cannot be an irrational number.
              </p>
             </li>
                </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>


    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Are the square roots of all positive integers irrational? 
              If not, give an example of the square root of a number that is a rational number.
            </p>
               </statement>
               <solution>
                <p>
                  No, the square roots of all positive integers are not irrational. For example, 
                  <m>\sqrt{4}</m> = 2 is rational. <m>\sqrt{9}</m> = 3 is rational. 
                  Hence, the square roots of positive integers 4 and 9 are not irrational.
                </p>
               </solution>
    </example>


